{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480794"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:51:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:51:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"110"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/110"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.08,0.47,0.18,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112872"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/110"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"110"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94909"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4626"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18238"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40947"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46422"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112872"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-hour history of sudden-onset visual disturbance. She has a medical history of angina and gout. Her regular medication is allopurinol. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 84/min and irregular, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals a left homonymous hemianopia. Cardiovascular examination reveals an irregularly irregular pulse with no murmurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG shows atrial fibrillation with a ventricular rate of 82/min. CT brain with angiogram and perfusion sequences reveals a small core infarct in the right posterior cerebral artery territory with a sizeable penumbra. She undergoes thrombolysis with alteplase.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate subsequent management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Warfarin lifelong","Aspirin and early pacemaker insertion","Aspirin for 48 hours then apixaban lifelong","Aspirin plus clopidogrel lifelong","Aspirin lifelong"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has suffered an ischaemic stroke, likely cardioembolic secondary to previously undiagnosed atrial fibrillation (AF). The small core infarct with preserved penumbra and isolated hemianopia suggests a minor-moderate stroke. Management involves both acute stroke treatment and secondary prevention strategies appropriate for AF-related stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin for 48 hours then apixaban lifelong\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. Following thrombolysis, aspirin should be withheld for 24 hours to reduce bleeding risk, then commenced. For minor-moderate strokes without significant haemorrhagic transformation, direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) such as apixaban can be initiated within 48 hours of stroke onset. This early initiation balances the risk of recurrent embolism against haemorrhagic transformation. DOACs are preferred over warfarin due to superior safety profiles and equivalent or better efficacy in stroke prevention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWarfarin lifelong\u003C/strong\u003E was previously standard therapy for AF-related stroke prevention. However, current Australian guidelines recommend DOACs as first-line anticoagulation due to reduced intracranial haemorrhage risk and no requirement for regular monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin and early pacemaker insertion\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated. The patient has AF, not a bradyarrhythmia requiring pacing. Aspirin alone is insufficient for stroke prevention in AF.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin plus clopidogrel lifelong\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate. While dual antiplatelet therapy is used acutely for minor strokes without AF, it does not provide adequate stroke prevention in patients with AF and carries increased bleeding risk with long-term use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin lifelong\u003C/strong\u003E alone is inadequate for secondary stroke prevention in AF. Studies demonstrate that anticoagulation reduces stroke risk by approximately 60% compared to aspirin in AF patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Direct oral anticoagulants can be commenced within 48 hours for minor to moderate ischaemic stroke in patients with atrial fibrillation without significant haemorrhagic transformation.","For major strokes, anticoagulation should be delayed until day six to seven to reduce the risk of haemorrhagic transformation.","Aspirin should be commenced within 48 hours of ischaemic stroke but not within 24 hours of thrombolysis."],"references":["Stroke Foundation. Clinical Guidelines for Stroke Management. Available at https://informme.org.au/guidelines/living-clinical-guidelines-for-stroke-management. Accessed [accessed 02/08/2025]"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94909"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"110"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18784"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id"